Here's the pattern using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In `App.xaml.cs` â€” override `CreateWindow` and use a custom Window:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}

public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        // Save draft when app backgrounds
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        // Restore draft when app returns
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

1. **`OnStopped`** fires when the app is fully backgrounded â€” save here.
2. **`OnResumed`** fires when returning from background â€” restore here.
3. **`OnDestroying`** is needed because Android's back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`.
4. **Keep handlers fast** (< 1â€“2 seconds). `Preferences` is ideal for small text. For large documents, use file I/O instead.
5. **Don't use `OnDeactivated`** for saving â€” it fires for dialogs/notification shade, not just backgrounding.
6. **`OnResumed` doesn't fire on first launch** â€” the initial sequence is `Created â†’ Activated`. Load any persisted draft in your page's constructor or `OnAppearing`.
